Data Cleaning

In the Boxoffice data we have revenue data for movie daywise, but number of days are not common for every movie

For example, movie A has revenue data for first 16 days while another movie B has revenue data for 23 days.

To solve this disparity,

  1. We will deal with only first 10 days revenue data for each movie and remove rest of the rows.

Number of rows left-

## [1] 34765
  1. We will remove movies that have only partial data for first 10 days revenue

url = as.character(movie_data[1,'Review_url'])
webpage <- read_html(url)
data <- html_nodes(webpage,'.e2kc3sl0')
data <- html_text(data)
if(length(data)==0){
  data <- html_nodes(webpage,'.story-content')
  data <- html_text(data)
}
if(length(data)!=0){
  review = ""
  for (para in data){
    review = paste(review,para)
  }
  review = data_frame(text = review)
}

Modelling

1) How well do New York Times (NYT) movie critics pick box office hits?

Movie Boxoffice Classification

We use the concept used by The Numbers website (as shown in the picture below) to classify the movie as Boxoffice hit or not.

Figure 3: An example from the number website (shaded area represent 95% movie data)

Steps:

  1. We will group the data day wise

  2. Our next step is to find a region in a plot (total_gross ~ days) where 95% of the movie data exist. We do this by using quantile function.

Above plots are histogram plots which are used to find total gross range day wise for 95% of the total movie

95% of films fall within the shaded area. If a film is in the dark yellow region, it has good legs compared to the average film and can be classifies as boxoffice hit.

(The predictive area is based on movies from the past 18 years)

Movies under consideration

## [1] 728

We will then classify movie as Boxoffice based on graph found in Exploratory Data Analysis.

We will now find the accuracy of the critic

X = Number of Movies picked up by critics

## [1] 117

Number of BoxOffice movies

## [1] 363

Number of Boxoffice movies (out of x)

## [1] 49

Accuracy

## [1] 42

Therefore we can say nearly 42% of the movies picked up by the critics were box office hit.

2) Is there a relationship between NYT movie review sentiment and critics picks?

Sementic analysis can be done on the review collected from NYTimes website.

Output would be positive, negative or neutral.

Since, both the variables are categorical

Hence, we can use Chi-Square test of independence to check whether two categorical variables from the same population are independent of each other or not.

Crammers V can then used later to find correlation that follows from this test.

movie Critic_Pick Review_url negative positive sentiment

The Avengers 0 http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/movies/robert-downey-jr-in-the-avengers-directed-by-joss-whedon.html 46 37 negative

Test the hypothesis whether the picking up of a movie by a critic is independent of movie review at .05 significance level.

## Warning in chisq.test(tbl): Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  tbl
## X-squared = 4, df = 2, p-value = 0.1

The warning message found in the solution above is due to the small cell values in the contingency table. To avoid such warning, we consider positive and neutral as positive and again apply chisq.test

##   [,1] [,2]
## 0  476  135
## 1   82   35
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  ctbl
## X-squared = 3, df = 1, p-value = 0.09

The p value 0.0868 is near to the significant level 0.05. Hence, we cannot say with certaninty that these value are independent of each other.

We can apply Crammers V test for better understanding of the association.

## [1] 0.063

Crammers V has output value between range 0 to 1.

0 depicting lowest association and 1 being higest.

Since, the output value is low we can say that Movie review has no or very less impact on Critic Pick

3) What characteristics of movies affect revenue?

We will use data frame as shown in Figure-3 to solve this problem.

We will focus on following features to find relationship with movies revenue

##  [1] "movie"         "total_gross"   "Critic_Pick"   "BoxOffice_Hit"
##  [5] "Year"          "Rated"         "Released"      "Runtime"      
##  [9] "Genre"         "Director"      "Writer"        "Actors"       
## [13] "Plot"          "Language"      "Country"       "Awards"       
## [17] "Metascore"     "imdbRating"    "imdbVotes"

Strategy -

For numerical data we will find coorelation coefficient

For categorical value we will find proportion distribution

Using above Correlation plot we can say-

  1. A high earning movie has higher number of Imdb votes.
  2. Box Office Hit movie earns a higher total revenue.
  3. Number of Languages, Runtime and imbdRating has a little influence on the Total revenue of the movie.

We further explore the relationship of categorical data with total Revenue

Null Hypothesis : Means of different moving rating are same or we can say Movie Rating does not affect its total Revenue

We now run one-way ANOVA (Analysis Of Variance) test to check the Null Hypothesis

##                    Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)    
## rating_data$Rated   7  153517   21931    7.69 6.4e-09 ***
## Residuals         616 1757014    2852                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

(A significance level of 0.05 indicates a 5% risk of concluding that a difference exists when there is no actual difference.)

F value is 8.11 and p-value is very low. Hence, we can reject the Null hypothesis and conclude that not all movie rating means are same.

However, ANOVA does not tells which groups are significantly different from other. Hence, we conduct TurkeyHSD (Tukey Honest Significant Differences) test

How to interpret above values -

  1. diff: difference between means of the two groups
  2. lwr, upr: the lower and the upper end point of the confidence interval at 95% (default)
  3. p adj: p-value after adjustment for the multiple comparisons.
  4. If the adjusted p value is less than 0.05, then the group has a signifant difference.

For example:

  1. There is no significance difference in total movie revinue( in million) between PG and G (P=0.61>0.05), Pg-13 and G (P=0.39>0.05). Similarly, the following groups have no significant difference.
